			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=DevCorner&message.id=12827#M12827">134</a> of 370
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1584 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<P><BR></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Grendalkhen wrote:<BR>
<DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Third, a class like a shaman or druid is extremly dependent on their gears focus effects.&nbsp; Due to both the offensive and defensive nature of these classes, they need to have focus effects of just about every type.&nbsp; This includes:<BR><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;healing focus<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;beneficial mana preservation<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;detrimental mana preservation<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;beneficial spell haste<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;detrimental spell haste<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;beneficial buff duration<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;detrimental debuff/dot duration<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;beneficial spell range (for heals)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;detrimental spell range (more for druid nukes)<BR><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Damage focus for shaman includes<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Magic (DoTs)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Poison (DDs, Rains, AEs, DoTs)<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cold (DD)<BR><BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Damage focus for druids includes<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fire<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cold<BR><BR>In PoP is wasnt too difficult to fill in a focus needs.&nbsp; This is because you had spell Focus that covered more then one line.&nbsp; Conservation of Xegony covered both bene and detri mana pres.&nbsp; Fury of Solusek covered all DDs (I dont believe DoT focus was in the game at this point).&nbsp;<BR><BR>But now, equiping a shaman has problems in items with different needed focus effects taking the same slot.&nbsp; If I want beneficial mana preservation (Avariciousness of the Ikaav) and I'm in a Anguish level guild (so Anguish minus OMM, Tacvi including Tunat, DoN through YarLir, DoDH - Shyra/Bloodeye) I have limited choices.&nbsp; They include the BP from Tunat, boots from MPG Trial of Adaptation (which isnt normally farmed), the Ring of Deterance from AMV in Ang, the Shroud of Surging Storm from Yarlir (very rare drop, think we have gotten 3 in 30kills).&nbsp; Now, if I got the MPG trial boots then I cant use Anguish boots which has Beneficial Mana pres.&nbsp; So I have to get that from somewhere else.&nbsp; If I wanted posion damage focus, for which there is only one gear option between the Tacvi/MPG level loot and Demi-plane, that being the Eye of Rikk from Rikk.&nbsp; This is a Range so this would force me to drop my Crystal staff which would force me to get a detrimental mana pres somewhere else.&nbsp; The Warbeads of the Magus are nice but then I would loose my beneficial spell haste from Necklace of Grimspirit Beads.&nbsp; So I have to find something else for that.<BR><BR>What I'm trying to point out here is casters have run into a jigsaw puzzle of items when they need to weigh Spell focus + item focus.&nbsp; Melee dont have to worry about this as Haste or ImpDodge or other melee centric needs dont denegrate and are not as needed.&nbsp; Additionally, for haste, a melee can just xp in a Skylance instance and wait for a 75HP/75mana/40%haste aug to drop...then they never have to worry about haste again.<BR><BR>Additionally, there are items in the game that make no sense or are just badly itemized.&nbsp; <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/item.html?id=47281" target=_blank>Belt of Contempt</A> for example off Ture.&nbsp; Its All/All but the focus effect applies to 3 classes (Shaman, SK, Necro) and of those 3, the shaman disease dots are worthless in a raid enviroment (and in general IMO).&nbsp; So you now have a All/all item which is just stats to almost all classes.&nbsp; Or shielding on Int caster only items (or even class items).&nbsp; The Mage head item from Qvic has 1% shielding on it.&nbsp; As a int caster, if they are getting hit, then shielding wont do them any good due to their crap AC and mitigation.&nbsp; Bracer of Grievous Harm from Tacvi has Fire damage focus on it.&nbsp; Since only Druids can use fire dmg of the 3 leather classes, its a useless focus for Beastlords; had the item had Cold dmg focus, then it would have been better itemized for the Leather Classes.&nbsp;&nbsp; Or Xxeric's Warbraid having Poison damage focus.&nbsp; Even though this item is for int casters, only Necros gain the benefit of the focus.&nbsp; If the Focus were fire, then 3 of the 4 classes could use...even better had the focus been magic based dmg, then every class who could wear could use.&nbsp; Finally, there are some caste only items that look like they were designed for melee only (think haste, atk and accuracy on a int caster item).<BR><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE></DIV></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>Perhaps it was unnecessary to repeat the bulk of this person's quote, but I think that it is such a major issue that it warrants it.&nbsp; I am speaking from a Shaman perspective here, but I know it can also apply to most of the other caster classes.</P>
<P>Shamen are a healing archetype, but depending on the nature of the encounter, we tend to take a bit more of an offensive role than clerics and druids, between debuffing, dotting, and the occasional nuking.&nbsp; But between buffing and being often the healer of DPS groups, we need to have a strong healing presence as well.&nbsp; This means that to play to our optimum, we have to have the entire range of beneficial and detrimental focus effects, as well as healing, magic, cold, and poison effects (and if you really want to include it, disease too).&nbsp; This can lead to absolute nightmares when trying to upgrade equipment, as Grendalkhen said better than I could.</P>
<P>In addition to this already existing nightmare, now we have an entirely new problem looming on the horizon, a level cap increase to 75.&nbsp; This means that all the focus effects we currently use are going to be significantly less effective.&nbsp; Even moreso if you still use items with the generic beneficial+detrimental focuses (Ikky BP comes to mind, since I haven't yet had the chance to upgrade it), the focus effects will be all but useless when dealing with level 75 spells.&nbsp; If a person isn't lucky enough to be in a guild able to raid endgame content shortly after the new expansion comes out, either they'll have to take a hit of several hundred, if not over a thousand, points of HP and Mana to upgrade their focus effects to ones that will work on the new spells, or they'll have to keep the equipment they have, maintaining a decent level of gear but being hampered with working with focus effects that either work much much less effectively or not at all.</P>
<P>And even if you are in a guild able to raid endgame content in the new expansion, we'll still have the nightmare of having to plan out exactly which items we need for which slots to get the whole, or even part, of the range of focus effects we need with the sheer number of focus effects we have to juggle around.</P>
<P>What I myself would love to see, is to have endgame level focus effects (Demiplane and Deathknell at the least, even better to include Dragons and Anguish level effects) have the level cap completely removed from them.&nbsp; I myself really don't see anything incredibly unbalancing with this, as it will make the game at least a bit more enjoyable without adding this extra hassle to have to deal with.&nbsp; It doesn't solve the problem that Grendalkhen mentioned, but it can save an even bigger problem later on down the road.</P>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
		<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
		 <span class=date_text>07-07-2006</span> <span class=time_text>10:44 AM</span>
		</span>
		</td>

		
